raw_response:
[
  {
    "message_type": "global",
    "content": "To all: The map is clear — England holds the west and can press everywhere if we coordinate. France is squeezed and likely to try a risky play (forecast indicates France has a 60% chance to act aggressively next phase toward Germany or elsewhere). That aggression creates an opportunity: if France attacks Germany, Germany will be distracted and we can push into the Low Countries/Germany without a long war at sea. I propose a short, explicit understanding: I will not push into Gascony or Brest this turn and will keep my fleets inactive toward the Bay if France stays focused on Germany. In return, I ask Germany (and any interested neutral parties) to refrain from cutting my Belgian/Holland positions so I can tie down German armies. This stabilizes the west and lets us all avoid a draining fight with France while we take more valuable centers elsewhere."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "FRANCE",
    "content": "AgentC — you are between a rock and a hard place. I see the forecast you sent to Germany suggesting a Machiavellian move; your projection shows a 60% chance you'll act aggressively. That aggression could be decisive for you if timed right, but it also exposes you to my fleets if it fails. My offer: I will stand down any fleet pushes toward Brest/Gascony this move and let you breathe in the west if you commit to NOT supporting any German holds into Burgundy or the Low Countries this turn, and to refrain from backstabs against England. If you truly intend aggression versus Germany (per your forecast), coordinate with me — I can use my armies in Belgium/Holland to pin German forces while you strike. This keeps your forecasted aggressive option viable without losing Brest/Picardy to opportunism."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "GERMANY",
    "content": "Agent? — France may well try a bold strike (I have credible intelligence indicating a 60% chance of French aggression toward Germany this phase). I will hold Belgium and Holland in support of stability in the Low Countries. If you agree to not try to seize Belgium/Holland this turn, I will not contest Denmark or attempt to break into the North Sea — we can steady the center and jointly deal with any French overreach. If France attacks you, accept my support in the Low Countries: I will keep A HOL and A BEL where they are and A DEN can assist KIE if needed. That gives you a safer flank to maneuver eastward."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "RUSSIA",
    "content": "Agent? — The Balkans are messy and Turkey/Austria are busy. I will not open hostilities toward the east so long as you do not move north into Scandinavia against my Norwegian/Swedish positions. Your pressure on Turkey is useful to me; if you can keep Turkey occupied, I will free up diplomatic bandwidth to oppose German consolidation in the north. Note: a forecasted French aggression to Germany increases the chance Germany pulls forces west — an opening you should exploit in the Baltic and Black Sea if possible."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "AUSTRIA",
    "content": "AgentB — Austria, you are under strain in the Balkans. I offer not to interfere with your southern front; in exchange, keep Turkey contested so they cannot divert fleets against me. The scenario suggests France might move aggressively and Germany could be distracted; this is your moment to shore up Vienna and press Trieste if you can. If Austria collapses, Turkey and Russia gain too much; let's coordinate to keep a balance there."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "ITALY",
    "content": "Friend — Italy, you have room to maneuver in the Med while the western powers sort themselves out. I will not contest Iberia further. Keep controlling the Mediterranean and consider pressuring Austria from the south if you see Austrian weakness. With France likely to act against Germany, Germany's attention eastward could be reduced — exploit that by expanding into neutral centers if safe."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "TURKEY",
    "content": "Agent? — Turkey, you and Russia are locked. I will not intervene in the eastern Med so long as you don't threaten the Italian south too aggressively. Note: forecasts indicate France’s likely aggression could tie Germany up in the west; that decreases the chance Germany aids Russia/Turkey via the Black Sea. Use this window to secure your gains, and if you need diplomatic space versus Russia/Austria, I can plausibly offer to pressure Germany in the north to keep them distracted."
  }
]

[
  {
    "message_type": "global",
    "content": "To all: France is on the ropes in 1915 and must act decisively. England controls the seas and threatens our western flank; Germany and Italy are opportunistic. I propose immediate, clear moves this month: I will strike to relieve pressure and create leverage. If you want stability in the west, now is the time to coordinate — otherwise I will be forced into aggressive actions to survive."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "ENGLAND",
    "content": "England — we both know you dominate the sea and can easily remove me if you oppose. I propose neutrality: I will not contest your northern or Iberian gains this year if you agree to leave Brest, Paris and Marseilles unmolested and refrain from supporting any attacks into Picardy or Gascony. If you accept, I will move to tie up my units defensively this turn and open diplomatic channels versus Germany. Note: forecast evidence (storyworld_forecast 'forecast_backstab') indicates a 60% chance Austria may act aggressively next phase. That increases the risk of an unstable blowup in the center — if you prefer continental chaos that distracts others, tacitly allowing a squeeze on England could be useful; if you prefer a clean west, honor the neutrality I request."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "GERMANY",
    "content": "Germany — France is weak but dangerous. I propose a short-term non-aggression: if you do not support any moves into Picardy, Burgundy or Belgium this year I will not assist England hitting Brest or Paris. I plan to use Brest offensively this turn (MAO or Gas) and close with Italy if you move into Burgundy. Also: storyworld forecast suggests Austria has a 60% chance to move aggressively next phase — that makes a coordinated German-Austrian push riskier and could open opportunities for us in the mid-game. Work with me to prevent Austria from gaining momentum."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "ITALY",
    "content": "Italy — you sit to our southeast and could be a valuable partner. I offer: I will not contest your holdings in Rome/Venice if you refrain from supporting any Austrian or Turkish pushes against me. In return I can pressure England's southern supply (Spain/Portugal) from Brest->MAO->POR or Brest->GAS->SPA this turn, creating distraction for Austria/Turkey and freeing you to secure the Adriatic. Note: I assess a moderate chance Austria will act aggressively next phase (forecast_backstab: 60% aggression). If Austria strikes, the balance in the Balkans shifts — better to align now."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "AUSTRIA",
    "content": "Austria — to survive I need a stable southeast. I propose neutrality between us: do not attack my southern flank or seek Italian support against me, and I will not contest your holdings in Vienna/Budapest/Serbia/Trentino. However, a forecast artifact suggests you are 60% likely to act aggressively next phase. If that is true, I urge caution: aggression will invite German or Russian counters and could force me into aligning with England or Italy to check you. Help me avoid that by standing down this phase and we can trade support and information."
  },
  {
    "message_type": "private",
    "recipient": "RUSSIA",
    "content": "Russia — you are heavily engaged in the Balkans and Black Sea. I do not want an immediate clash with you over neutral centers, but I need breathing room in the west. I will take one of three actions from Brest this move (MAO to threaten Portugal, GAS to threaten Spain, or PIC to pressure England's northern armies). Tell me which target would most hinder England for you and I will pursue it; in return I ask you not to push into Galicia or support Austrian aggression against me. Note: forecast_backstab indicates Austria may act aggressively (60%); if Austria moves now it could change our continental priorities quickly."
  }
]
